The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 Sambaran penalised for dereliction of duties

Mumbai: The Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) cracked the whip on its erring officials Match Referee Sambaran Banerjee and umpire Sameer Bandekar on Monday for dereliction of duties during the first round Ranji Trophy Elite tie in Delhi between Delhi and Uttar Pradesh. 

The umpires sub-committee of the BCCI, at its meeting here on Monday under the chairmanship of BCCI vice-president Lalit Modi, has decided not to allot any more matches during the season for former Bengal stumper and national selector Banerjee and Mumbais Bandekar. 

The two officials had left midway through suspension of play due to bad light during the Ranji match played from December 1-4 and were not present for inspection of light conditions, preferring to watch an under-22 game at a nearby ground. 

Announcing the decision of the sub-committee, BCCIs joint secretary and convenor MP Pandove said the committee had taken a decision not to give any more matches during the remainder of the season to Banerjee and Bandekar. We have taken the decision on the basis of reports that we have received from the staging association (Delhi and District Cricket Association), the rival captains and media coverage of the incident, Pandove said. (PTI) 




